# appkit-mastra patterns

## Agent registration

Use `createAgent` (identity helper for type inference) + `tool`
(AppKit-shaped factory). Reach for `createTool` only when you need
Mastra-only fields (`outputSchema`, `suspendSchema`,
`requireApproval`, `mcp`).

```ts
import { createAgent, tool } from "@dbx-tools/appkit-mastra";

const support = createAgent({
  instructions: "...",
  tools(plugins) {
    return {
      ...plugins.analytics.toolkit(),
      ...plugins.files.toolkit({ only: ["uploads.read"] }),
      get_weather: tool({ description, schema, execute }),
    };
  },
});
```

## Writer events are flat

Mastra `ctx.writer` events use a flat `{ type, ...fields }` shape;
subscribers narrow on `event.type` and read fields inline. The
unified vocabulary lives in `@dbx-tools/appkit-mastra-shared` as
`GenieWriterEvent` (wire-derived `GenieChatEvent` ∪ Mastra-only
`GenieAgentEvent`).

Always publish through `safeWrite` (see `dry-helpers` rule).

## Chart pipeline

Inline charts use the `[chart:<chartId>]` marker pattern. Two
producers, one wire format:

- `render_data` tool: generic dataset → chart. Mints a `chartId`,
  awaits `runChartPlanner`, emits one `type: "chart"` writer event
  with both `data` + resolved `option`, returns `{ chartId }` to
  the LLM.
- Genie agent: per-statement charting inside its workflow finalize
  step. Same writer event shape.

The Echarts spec lives off-band on `RequestContext` (via
`recordChartInContext`) so downstream processors / tools can look
up the full spec by `chartId` without re-fetching or re-planning.
The LLM-bound payload stays flat regardless of dataset size.

## Genie agent (vs the stock AppKit `genie` plugin)

`appkit-mastra`'s Genie integration talks to Genie **directly** via
`@dbx-tools/genie` (`genieEventChat`) and
`statementExecution.getStatement`. AppKit's stock `genie()` plugin
is honored only for its `spaces` config and the matching
`app.yaml`-declared resources.

Tool ids:
- `genie` for the `"default"` alias
- `genie_<alias>` for additional aliases

## Conversation caching

Per-user Genie conversation ids are persisted via `CacheManager`
(AppKit's TTLCache equivalent) with sliding-TTL semantics. The
stale-id recovery path (404 on follow-up) evicts the cache, clears
the per-request context, and retries the turn once.

## Workspace and Assistant skills

Every `createAgent` call defaults `workspace` to `createWorkspace()`
([`workspaces.ts`](src/workspaces.ts)). The workspace exposes a
per-request composite filesystem backed by the OBO
`WorkspaceClient` ([`filesystems.ts`](src/filesystems.ts)).

With the default (`assistantSkills: true`), each request mounts:

| Databricks path | Workspace mount | Purpose |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `/Workspace/.assistant/skills` | `/workspace_skills` | Shared Assistant skills |
| `/Users/<email>/.assistant/skills` | `/workspace_user_skills` | Per-user skills |

Mounts are read-only. Production requires `workspace` or `all-apis` on
the forwarded access token (`tokenUtils.getAccessTokenScopes` stamped as
`MASTRA_SCOPES_KEY` by [`server.ts`](src/server.ts)); development
(`NODE_ENV=development`) skips the scope check. Mastra scans mounted
paths for `SKILL.md` files.

```ts
import { createAgent, createWorkspace } from "@dbx-tools/appkit-mastra";

// Default: Assistant skills on (no explicit workspace needed).
const support = createAgent({ instructions: "..." });

// Custom mounts alongside Assistant skills.
const analyst = createAgent({
  instructions: "...",
  workspace: createWorkspace({
    assistantSkills: true,
    mounts: [
      async ({ requestContext }) => ({
        mounts: { "/data": myFilesystem },
        skillPaths: [],
      }),
    ],
  }),
});

// Opt out of built-in skill mounts.
const bare = createAgent({
  instructions: "...",
  workspace: createWorkspace({ assistantSkills: false }),
});
```

`createWorkspace`, `DatabricksWorkspaceFilesystem`, `emptyFilesystem`,
and Databricks path helpers are exported from this package for apps that
need direct filesystem access or tests.
